  "prompt": "Cost for 1kg of A is 260 USD and 1kg of B is 380. AB is made by mixing A and B. If 1kg of AB costs 300, what was the ratio that A and B has mixed?",
  "response": "To determine the ratio in which A and B were mixed to form AB costing 300 USD per kg, we can set up an equation based on the costs and the mixture.\n\nLet's denote the weights of A and B in the mixture as \\( x \\) kg and \\( y \\) kg, respectively.\n\nThe cost of 1 kg of AB can be expressed as a weighted average of the costs of A and B:\n\\[\n\\frac{260x + 380y}{x + y} = 300\n\\]\n\nFirst, multiply both sides by \\( x + y \\) to clear the denominator:\n\\[\n260x + 380y = 300(x + y)\n\\]\n\nNext, expand and simplify the equation:\n\\[\n260x + 380y = 300x + 300y\n\\]\n\nRearrange the equation to isolate the terms involving \\( x \\) and \\( y \\):\n\\[\n260x + 380y - 300x - 300y = 0\n\\]\n\\[\n-40x + 80y = 0\n\\]\n\nFactor out the common term:\n\\[\n40(-x + 2y) = 0\n\\]\n\\[\n-x + 2y = 0\n\\]\n\nSolving for \\( x \\) and \\( y \\), we get:\n\\[\nx = 2y\n\\]\n\nThis indicates that the ratio of A to B in the mixture is \\( x : y = 2 : 1 \\).\n\nTherefore, A and B were mixed in the ratio of 2:1.",
